# Frontend Rules

## Framework

- Svelte 5 with SvelteKit 2
- Tailwind CSS v4 (utility-first, no component CSS files)
- TypeScript strict mode
- Icons from `lucide-svelte`
- Markdown rendering with `marked`

## Svelte 5 Runes

Always use runes, never legacy Svelte syntax:
- `$state` for reactive variables
- `$derived` / `$derived.by` for computed values
- `$props()` for component props (typed)
- `$effect` for side effects
- `$bindable()` for two-way bindable props

## Component Conventions

- Props are typed inline with `$props()`:
  ```svelte
  let { article, onOpen, onToggleSave }: Props = $props();
  ```
- Callbacks use `on*` naming: `onOpen`, `onBack`, `onToggleSave`, `onSendChat`
- Components never manage global state — state flows down via props, events flow up via callbacks

## State Management

- All app state lives in `+page.svelte` using `$state`
- No Svelte stores — keep it simple and co-located
- `localStorage` for caching (`axon_premium_cache`) and saved articles (`axon_saved_signals`)

## Styling

- Dark theme: backgrounds `#0b0b0b` / `#0a0a0a`, text `#e4e4e7`
- Fonts: Inter (body), JetBrains Mono (code)
- Use Tailwind classes exclusively — no inline styles, no `<style>` blocks (except global overrides in `+page.svelte`)
- Responsive: desktop = sidebar + feed + reader side-by-side; mobile = bottom nav + feed, reader overlays full-screen

## File Organization

- Components grouped by feature: `feed/`, `navigation/`, `reader/`
- Shared logic in `lib/api.ts` (API client) and `lib/ui.ts` (navigation, helpers)
- One route: `+page.svelte` is the entire app

## API Client

All backend calls go through `$lib/api.ts`. Never call `fetch()` directly in components — always use the `api` object.
